    content: `
      <h2>The Statute with Teeth</h2>
      <p>Most importers do not realize that a simple clerical error can trigger a federal penalty case that threatens the solvency of their business. Under 19 U.S.C. § 1592, CBP can penalize any material false statement or omission made in connection with an entry. Crucially, you do not have to <em>intend</em> to cheat the government. If you were just sloppy - "negligent" - you are liable for massive civil penalties.</p>
      
      <h2>The Three Levels of Culpability</h2>
      <p>The severity of the penalty depends on the level of culpability CBP assigns to your actions:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Negligence:</strong> You failed to exercise reasonable care. This is the catch-all. The penalty cap is 2x the loss of duty (or 20% of value if no duty lost).</li>
        <li><strong>Gross Negligence:</strong> You acted with "wanton disregard" for the facts or failed to verify information despite red flags. The penalty cap is 4x the loss of duty (or 40% of value).</li>
        <li><strong>Fraud:</strong> You intentionally deceived CBP. The penalty cap is the full domestic value of the goods. For a regular importer, this can easily reach into the tens of millions of dollars.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>Our first move in defense is attacking the culpability level. CBP often overcharges, alleging Fraud or Gross Negligence when the facts only support Negligence (or no violation at all). We force them to prove intent, often getting the charges downgraded to simple negligence or technical violations.</p>

      <h2>Prior Disclosure: The "Get Out of Jail" Card</h2>
      <p>If you find an error before CBP does, you have a powerful tool: the "Prior Disclosure" under 1592(c)(4). If filed correctly, this limits your liability to the interest on the unpaid duties. The penalty is wiped out completely. However, the timing is critical. If CBP has already started a formal investigation, the disclosure window closes. We advise clients on exactly when and how to disclose to secure this safe harbor without alerting CBP to issues they wouldn't have found otherwise.</p>

      <h2>The Petition Process and Mitigation</h2>
      <p>If CBP issues a Pre-Penalty Notice, the fight is not over. We file a response challenging the facts and the law. If a penalty is assessed, we file a Petition for Mitigation under 19 U.S.C. § 1618. CBP guidelines (19 CFR Part 171, Appendix B) allow for mitigation based on factors like: inexperience, lack of prior violations, contributory government error, and inability to pay. We draft comprehensive petitions that paint the full picture, often negotiating settlements that reduce six-figure penalties to nominal amounts or warning letters.</p>
    `
