    content: `
      <h2>The Transaction Value Trap</h2>
      <p>Most importers use "Transaction Value" - the price actually paid or payable for the goods. It sounds simple: declare what you paid the factory. But under 19 U.S.C. § 1401a, the "price" includes far more than the check you wrote for the goods. If you miss these additions, you are undervaluing your goods, and CBP will view that as a revenue loss violation subject to penalties.</p>

      <h2>The "Assist" Problem</h2>
      <p>Here is the classic scenario: You pay for a mold or die here in the U.S. ($50,000) and ship it to your factory in China to use in production. You don't charge the factory for it. That mold is an "Assist." Its value must be apportioned and added to the declared value of the imported goods. We see companies miss this constantly. The finance team books it as an asset, but the logistics team never tells the customs broker. When CBP finds it during an audit, they go back 5 years and calculate the unpaid duties plus interest and penalties.</p>

      <h2>Related Party Pricing and Transfer Pricing</h2>
      <p>If you are buying from a subsidiary or parent company overseas, CBP is immediately suspicious. They assume the price is artificially low to save on duties. You bear the burden of proving that the relationship did not influence the price - that it is an "arm's length" transaction. </p>
      <p>Many companies rely on their IRS Transfer Pricing Study to prove this. This is a mistake. IRS rules (maximize profit in low-tax jurisdictions) and Customs rules (maximize value for duty purposes) often conflict. We work with your tax and finance teams to reconcile your Transfer Pricing policies with Customs valuation rules, creating a defense file that satisfies both agencies.</p>

      <h2>First Sale for Export: A Strategy for Savings</h2>
      <p>On the flip side, you might be overpaying. If you buy from a middleman/vendor who buys from a factory, you are paying duties on the middleman's markup. The "First Sale" rule allows you to base duties on the price the factory charged the middleman, rather than the price the middleman charged you. </p>
      <p>Implementing this requires rigorous documentation to prove the goods were "destined" for the U.S. from the start. We help clients structure these multi-tiered transactions to legally lower the dutiable basis, resulting in millions of dollars in annual duty savings.</p>
    `
