  content: `
<h2>Regulatory Framework for Prior Disclosure Timing</h2>

<p>The prior disclosure provision under 19 U.S.C. § 1592(c)(4) establishes specific timing parameters that determine both the validity and effectiveness of voluntary disclosures to U.S. Customs and Border Protection. A valid prior disclosure must disclose the circumstances of a violation before, or without knowledge of, the commencement of a formal investigation by CBP. This temporal requirement creates the fundamental tension underlying all timing strategies: the need for comprehensive disclosure documentation versus the risk of CBP initiating investigative action.</p>

<p>Under 19 CFR § 162.74, the regulatory implementation provides additional timing specifications. The regulation establishes a 30-day perfection period from the initial disclosure date, during which importers must provide any information or data unknown at the time of initial filing. This perfection mechanism allows importers to submit an initial disclosure to preserve their prior disclosure rights while continuing to gather comprehensive supporting documentation. The Fines, Penalties, and Forfeitures Officer may extend this 30-day period upon showing of good cause, though such extensions remain discretionary.</p>

<h2>Determining CBP Commencement of Formal Investigation</h2>

<p>The commencement of a formal investigation represents the critical cutoff point for prior disclosure eligibility. Under 19 CFR § 162.74(b), a formal investigation is considered to have commenced on the date recorded in writing by CBP when facts and circumstances were discovered or information was received that caused CBP to believe a possibility of violation existed. This definition encompasses both affirmative investigative actions and passive receipt of information suggesting violations.</p>

<p>Knowledge of commencement becomes presumed under specific circumstances outlined in the regulation. When CBP informs the person of the type of or circumstances of the disclosed violation, when a Customs Special Agent makes an inquiry concerning the violation, or when CBP issues a pre-penalty or penalty notice, the disclosing party is charged with knowledge of the investigation. Importantly, even specific questioning by a CBP Officer regarding a suspected violation may constitute commencement, creating risk for importers who delay filing while attempting to gather perfect information.</p>

<p>California importers face particular challenges at the Los Angeles/Long Beach Seaport complex, where the high volume of entries and sophisticated enforcement presence increases the likelihood of CBP discovering violations through routine examinations, data analytics, or industry-focused enforcement initiatives. The ports' role as the primary gateway for Asian imports subjects entries to enhanced scrutiny under various priority trade programs, accelerating the timeline for potential investigation commencement.</p>

<h2>Tender Requirements and Financial Timing Considerations</h2>

<p>The tender requirement under 19 CFR § 162.74(c) imposes specific timing obligations based on the nature of the disclosed violation. For violations resulting from negligence or gross negligence, the disclosing party must tender the unpaid amount of lawful duties, taxes, and fees either at the time of disclosure or within 30 days after CBP's written notification of its calculation of the unpaid amount. This dual-option structure allows importers to either calculate and tender immediately or await CBP's determination, though the latter approach extends the period of uncertainty.</p>

<p>The financial implications of timing decisions extend beyond the tender amount itself. Under 19 U.S.C. § 1592(c)(4), a valid prior disclosure for negligent or grossly negligent violations reduces the penalty to the interest on the duty underpayment, calculated from the date of liquidation to the date of collection. This interest-only penalty structure creates significant incentive for early disclosure, as the alternative penalties range from one to four times the duty loss for negligence and gross negligence respectively. For fraudulent violations, prior disclosure reduces penalties from the domestic value of merchandise to the actual duty loss, or if no duty loss exists, to 10% of the dutiable value.</p>

<h2>Strategic Filing Windows and Decision Points</h2>

<p>The optimal filing window balances multiple competing factors unique to each violation scenario. Immediate disclosure upon discovery minimizes the risk of CBP commencement but may result in incomplete or inaccurate disclosure requiring substantial amendment. Conversely, delaying to ensure comprehensive documentation increases the probability of CBP discovering the violation through audit, examination, or data analysis programs.</p>

<p>California importers should evaluate several decision points when determining filing timing. First, assess the violation's detectability through CBP's automated targeting systems and industry-focused enforcement priorities. Violations involving common compliance issues in targeted industries face higher discovery risk, warranting accelerated disclosure timelines. Second, consider the complexity of calculating duty loss across multiple entries and ports, particularly for systematic errors requiring extensive record review. Third, evaluate the availability of knowledgeable personnel and documentation, as staff turnover or inadequate record retention may necessitate protective disclosure strategies.</p>

<p>The 30-day perfection period offers strategic flexibility for complex violations. Importers can file an initial disclosure identifying the general nature and scope of violations, preserving prior disclosure eligibility while conducting detailed entry-by-entry reviews. This approach proves particularly valuable for multi-year violations requiring extensive documentation retrieval and duty recalculation.</p>

<h2>California Port Procedures and Multi-Port Coordination</h2>

<p>Prior disclosures involving California ports must be submitted to both the Fines, Penalties and Forfeitures office at the port where violations occurred and the appropriate Center of Excellence and Expertise. For the Los Angeles/Long Beach Seaport complex, submissions should be directed to the FP&F office at 301 E. Ocean Blvd., Suite 1400, Long Beach, CA 90802, with conspicuous marking of "PRIOR DISCLOSURE" on all correspondence.</p>

<p>Multi-port violations requiring disclosure at both California and other ports present coordination challenges. The regulation permits listing all concerned ports in a single disclosure, facilitating CBP's consolidation at a single location. However, importers must ensure timely submission to all affected ports, as failure to disclose at any location where violations occurred may invalidate the entire disclosure. California importers with violations spanning the Los Angeles, Long Beach, San Francisco, and San Diego ports should coordinate submission timing to ensure simultaneous receipt across all locations.</p>

<h2>Protective Disclosure Strategies</h2>

<p>Protective disclosures serve as insurance against unexpected CBP enforcement actions during internal compliance reviews. Upon discovering potential violations during routine audits or compliance assessments, importers may file protective disclosures identifying the general nature of suspected violations while investigation continues. This strategy proves particularly valuable when violations appear systemic but require extensive analysis to quantify.</p>

<p>The protective disclosure strategy requires careful drafting to avoid admitting violations that may not exist while providing sufficient detail to preserve prior disclosure benefits if violations are confirmed. The initial disclosure should identify the specific regulatory provisions potentially violated, the time period under review, and the universe of entries potentially affected. California importers should reference specific entry numbers filed through California ports when known, as CBP's entry data systems facilitate verification of disclosure scope.</p>

<h2>Oral Disclosure Confirmation Requirements</h2>

<p>While prior disclosures may be submitted orally to CBP officers, 19 CFR § 162.74(a)(2) requires written confirmation within 10 days of the oral disclosure date. This abbreviated timeline demands immediate preparation of written documentation following any oral disclosure, whether made during examination, audit, or other CBP interaction. California importers making oral disclosures at the Los Angeles/Long Beach ports should obtain the receiving officer's name and badge number, documenting the exact date, time, and location of the disclosure for the required written confirmation.</p>

<h2>Interest Calculation Methodologies</h2>

<p>The interest-based penalty structure for prior disclosures requires precise calculation methodologies. Interest accrues from the date of liquidation for each affected entry through the date of duty payment, using the rates established under Internal Revenue Code provisions. For entries liquidated over extended periods, the varying interest rates create complex calculations requiring entry-by-entry analysis. California importers should maintain spreadsheets tracking liquidation dates, duty amounts, and applicable interest rates for each entry included in the disclosure.</p>

<p>The timing of tender submission affects total interest liability, as continued accrual occurs until CBP receives payment. Importers choosing immediate tender must calculate interest through the anticipated payment receipt date, while those awaiting CBP calculation face ongoing accrual until CBP's determination and subsequent payment. This dynamic creates incentive for rapid tender following disclosure, particularly for older violations with substantial accrued interest.</p>

<h2>Conclusion</h2>

<p>Prior disclosure timing strategies under 19 U.S.C. § 1592(c)(4) and 19 CFR § 162.74 require careful evaluation of competing priorities and risks. California importers must balance the need for comprehensive disclosure against the constant risk of CBP investigation commencement, while navigating complex tender requirements and multi-port coordination challenges. The substantial penalty mitigation available through valid prior disclosure justifies strategic planning and, when circumstances warrant, protective filing approaches that preserve disclosure rights during ongoing compliance reviews. Success requires understanding both the regulatory framework and practical enforcement patterns at California's major ports, enabling informed decisions that maximize penalty mitigation while ensuring disclosure validity.</p>
`
